    <div xml:id="PN360">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>peritārāc ciṟuciṉattar</l>
<l>cilacollāṟ palakēḷviyar</l>
<l>nuṇṇuṇarviṉāṟ peruṅkoṭaiyar</l>
<l>kaluḻnaṉaiyāṟ ṟaṇṭēṟalar</l>
<l>kaṉikuyyāṟ koḻuntuvaiyar</l>
<l>tāḻuvantu taḻūumoḻiyar</l>
<l>payaṉuṟuppap palarkkāṟṟi</l>
<l>yēma māka vinnila māṇṭōr</l>
<l>cilarē peruma kēḷiṉi nāḷum</l>
<l>palarē takaiyaḵ taṟiyā tōrē</l>
<l>yaṉṉōr celvamu maṉṉi nillā</l>
<l>tiṉṉu maṟṟataṉ paṇpē yataṉāl</l>
<l>niccamu moḻukka muṭṭilai paricil</l>
<l>naccuvar kaiyi ṉirappa lōmpumati</l>
<l>yaccuvarap</l>
<l>pāṟiṟai koṇṭa paṟantalai mākata</l>
<l>kaḷḷi pōkiya kaḷari maruṅkiṉ</l>
<l>veḷḷi ṉiṟutta piṉṟaik kaḷḷoṭu</l>
<l>pullakat tiṭṭa cillaviḻ valci</l>
<l>pulaiya ṉēvap puṉmē lamarntuṇ</l>
<l>ṭaḻalvāyp pukka piṉṉum</l>
<l>palarvāyt tirāar paruttuṇ ṭōrē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Those with little anger that is not fully satiated, (1)</l>
<l>those who listen to many [words] by means of few words, (2)</l>
<l>those with great gifts through subtle understanding, (3) </l>
<l>those with cool toddy [spiced] with turbid buds, (4)</l>
<l>those with fat meat with fruity seasoning, (5)</l>
<l>those with words that embrace, rejoicing at bowing down, (6)</l>
<l>appeasing to many people to make them have the yield, (7)</l>
<l>those who rule this ground so that it is protected (8)</l>
<l>are but few, great man – now listen: daily (9)</l>
<l>there are many who do now know that that is befitting, (10)</l>
<l>and the riches of suchlike, having lasted, are not permanent. (11)</l>
<l>Even now [that] is the nature of that. Therefore, (12)</l>
<l>You are no hindrance to the daily conduct. (13a-c)</l>
<l>Beware of filling the hands of those who covet gifts. (13d-14)</l>
<l>When fear comes, (15)</l>
<l>o minstrel in the waste land where the kites took a seat, (16)</l>
<l>in the saline soil where the spurge has gone large, (17)</l>
<l>after they have been placed on the bier, for food </l>
<l>a little rice that is placed in the grass, along with toddy, (18f.)</l>
<l>and after, when the Pulaiyaṉ gives the command, they remained</l>
<l>on the grass [and] entered the mouth of the fire, being eaten, (20f.)</l>
<l>they don’t remain, being superior(?) to many, those eaten by kites. (22)</l>
</lg>
